                <fr:taxon>Side note</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>Kleene (pronounced "CLAY-nee") was a 20th-century US logician.
    His son would later say, of the pronunciation CLAY-nee, "As far as I am aware this pronunciation is incorrect in all known languages. I believe that this novel pronunciation was invented by my father".
    (See <fr:link href="https://foldoc.org/Stephen+Kleene" type="external">https://foldoc.org/Stephen+Kleene</fr:link>.)</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <html:p>    This is a very widely used and studied structure, and it's one we'll use a lot this semester.
</html:p>
            <html:p>    Indeed, this structure is so widely used and studied that there's not really any single fixed interpretation we can give to the value <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex>.
    Sometimes people think of it as "neither true nor false", sometimes as "both true and false", sometimes as "half true", sometimes as "an unknown truth value", and sometimes in other ways.
    But however it is interpreted, the structure is the same.
    For now, pay attention just to the structure itself.
</html:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="/lectures/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>3</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>14</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/004H/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>004H</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/lectures/004H/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Looking at a structure without interpreting it">Looking at a structure without interpreting it</fr:title>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>        Even without any interpretation at all for the value <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex>, we can still see how the strong Kleene structure works, and we can build up strong Kleene valuations using this structure in just the way you would expect.
        (Again, you have exercises on this at <fr:link href="https://binchicken.one/" type="external">https://binchicken.one</fr:link>.)
        The same is true of the values <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}, \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex>; you don't need to think of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex> as connecting to truth, or of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex> as connecting to falsity, to be able to see how the strong Kleene structure works in full.
</html:p>
                <html:p>        Indeed, you don't need to think of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}, \mathsf {\mathbf {*}}, \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex> as <html:em>truth</html:em> values at all; let's just call them "values".
        All you need, in order to be able to use the structure, is to know how connectives act on these values.
        That information is contained entirely in the above tables.
        So you don't need to interpret this structure at all to be able to use it.
</html:p>
                <html:p>        The same is true of all our structures.
        Although I've tried to help you get the feel for the Boolean structure and the Dunn-Belnap structure by having you think about truth and falsity, the structures themselves don't depend on this way of interpreting them.
        All the structures really are is some collection of values and a way to calculate on them using the connectives.
</html:p>
                <html:p>        This is why we're able to use these structures for purposes other than thinking about truth.
        Recall our electrical interpretation of the Boolean structure.
        A switch that's on isn't <html:em>true</html:em>, and a switch that's off isn't <html:em>false</html:em>; they're just on or off.
        But we used the value <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex> to represent being on and the value <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex> to represent being off.
        This required divorcing <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex> from their initial interpretation as truth values.
</html:p>
                <html:p>        Similarly when we think about the epistemic interpretation of the Dunn-Belnap structure.
        You might have been told both that Carl is a good dog and that Carl's not a good dog, and we can use the value <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {B}}]]></fr:tex> to keep track of that.
        But that doesn't mean that "Carl is a good dog" <html:em>really is</html:em> both true and false.
        (In fact, it's not false at all!)
        So in this interpretation, we're using the values as records of reports, again not as truth values.
        It's possible to interpret these structures in many different ways because the structures themselves don't depend on any particular interpretation; they're fully abstract.</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="/lectures/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>3</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>14</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/004I/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>004I</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/lectures/004I/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Relabeling structures">Relabeling structures</fr:title>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>        So if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex> don't have to have anything to do with truth and falsity, why are they called "<fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex>" and "<fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex>"?
        Here's the real answer: well, we had to call them <html:em>something</html:em>, and the suggestion of truth and falsity carried by the names "<fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex>" and "<fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex>" can be useful for building your intuition, as long as you don't get stuck on the idea.
        The same goes for the values <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {N}}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {B}}]]></fr:tex>, and the names "<fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {N}}]]></fr:tex>" and "<fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {B}}]]></fr:tex>" we're using for them.
        Once you're familiar with these structures, the names for the values don't matter at all.
        We could easily use different names.
</html:p>
                <html:p>        For example, <fr:link href="/lectures/003T/" title="Zeroes and ones" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/003T/" display-uri="003T" type="local">sometimes people will present the Boolean structure using the names "1" and "0"</fr:link> for its values, rather than "<fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex>" and "<fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex>", as I've done here.
        But it's still the same structure, so long as all the connectives behave the same way.
        For example, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg  1 = 0]]></fr:tex>, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[1 \lor  0 = 1]]></fr:tex>, and so on.
        We're just calling the values something different; as long as they act the same the difference doesn't matter.
</html:p>
                <html:p>        In thinking about all of our structures, then, it can be helpful to open up a part of your mind that lets you think about them without any particular interpretation in view, and even without any particular names for the values in view, since these names are often linked to particular interpretations.
        As much as you can, try to just think about the values themselves and how the connectives operate on them, separate from any ideas about truth, or electricity, or possible worlds.
</html:p>
                <html:p>        It's by proceeding in such an abstract way, separate from all applications, that we can get away with doing the work just once.
        It can then be applied over and over, wherever we want it.
        The logician Rósza Péter put the point this way (emphasis added): 
</html:p>
                <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
                  <fr:frontmatter>
                    <fr:authors>
                      <fr:author>
                        <fr:link href="/lectures/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
                      </fr:author>
                    </fr:authors>
                    <fr:date>
                      <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                      <fr:month>3</fr:month>
                      <fr:day>14</fr:day>
                    </fr:date>
                    <fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/004J/</fr:uri>
                    <fr:display-uri>004J</fr:display-uri>
                    <fr:route>/lectures/004J/</fr:route>
                    <fr:taxon>Quotation</fr:taxon>
                  </fr:frontmatter>
                  <fr:mainmatter>
                    <html:p>        "Mathematics is really a language, a queer language which speaks entirely in symbols. 
            The above formula is only a symbol, and means nothing by itself; everybody can substitute into it [their] own experiences. 
            For one it might mean the counting of the diagonals of a polygon, for another the counting of the number of possibilities for choosing the leading pair among [their] pupils. 
            <html:em>The writing down of a formula is an expression of our joy</html:em> that we can answer all these questions by means of one argument."
</html:p>
                    <html:p>From Rósza Péter, <html:em>Playing With Infinity</html:em>, 1955</html:p>
                  </fr:mainmatter>
                </fr:tree>
                <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
                  <fr:frontmatter>
                    <fr:authors>
                      <fr:author>
                        <fr:link href="/lectures/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
                      </fr:author>
                    </fr:authors>
                    <fr:date>
                      <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                      <fr:month>3</fr:month>
                      <fr:day>14</fr:day>
                    </fr:date>
                    <fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/004K/</fr:uri>
                    <fr:display-uri>004K</fr:display-uri>
                    <fr:route>/lectures/004K/</fr:route>
                    <fr:taxon>Side note</fr:taxon>
                  </fr:frontmatter>
                  <fr:mainmatter>
                    <html:p>Rósza Péter was a Hungarian logician in the mid-20th century.
Her work was particularly important in the development of an area of logic known as "recursion theory".
(See <fr:link href="https://plato.stanford.edu/entries/recursive-functions/" type="external">the Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy article here</fr:link> for an introduction.)</html:p>
                  </fr:mainmatter>
                </fr:tree>
                <html:p>"The writing down of a formula is an expression of our joy".
I think Péter has hit the nail on the head.</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
